The '''olive-naped weaver''' ('''''Ploceus brachypterus''''') is a bird species in the family [[Ploceidae]]. It is found in [[West Africa]] from Senegal and Gambia to Cameroon.

==Taxonomy==
The olive-naped weaver was [[species description|formally described]] and illustrated in 1837 by the English naturalist [[William Swainson]]. He did not specify the origin of his specimens but they probably came from Senegal. He placed the species in the genus ''[[Ploceus]]'' and coined the [[binomial name]] ''Ploceus brachypterus''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Swainson | first=William | author-link=William Swainson | year=1837 | title=The Natural History of the Birds of Western Africa | volume=1 | location=Edinburgh | publisher=W.H. Lizars | page=168; Plate 10 | url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_FAwAAAAAQAAJ/page/n206/mode/1up }}</ref><ref>{{ cite book | editor1-last=Mayr | editor1-first=Ernst | editor1-link=Ernst Mayr  | editor2-last=Greenway | editor2-first=James C. Jr | year=1962 | title=Check-List of Birds of the World | volume=15 | publisher=Museum of Comparative Zoology | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts | page=38 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14485411 }}</ref> The specific epithet is from [[Ancient Greek]] ''brakhupteros'' meaning "short-winged".<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4 | page=[https://archive.org/stream/Helm_Dictionary_of_Scientific_Bird_Names_by_James_A._Jobling#page/n76/mode/1up 76] }}</ref>

The olive-naped weaver was formerly considered to be a [[subspecies]] of the [[black-necked weaver]] ''(Ploceus nigricollis'').<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | date=January 2023 | title=Old World sparrows, snowfinches, weavers | work=IOC World Bird List Version 13.1 | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/weavers/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=7 February 2023 }}</ref> The two species differ in plumage and in the colour of the iris,<ref name=bow>{{cite journal | last1=Kirwan | first1=G.M. | last2=Craig | first2=A.J.F. |  last3=del Hoyo | first3=J. | last4=Collar | first4=N. | date=2022 | title=Olive-naped Weaver (''Ploceus brachypterus''), version 1.0 | editor1-last=Billerman | editor1-first=S.M. | editor2-last=Sly | editor2-first=N.D. | journal=Birds of the World | location=Ithaca, NY, USA | publisher=Cornell Lab of Ornithology | doi=10.2173/bow.bknwea1.01 }}</ref> but a molecular study published in 2019 found that they are genetically very similar.<ref>{{Cite journal | last1=De Silva | first1=T.N. | last2=Peterson | first2=A.T. | last3=Perktas | first3=U. | date=2019 | title=An extensive molecular phylogeny of weaverbirds (Aves: Ploceidae) unveils broad nonmonophyly of traditional genera and new relationships | journal=The Auk | volume=136 | issue=ukz041 | doi=10.1093/auk/ukz041 | doi-access= }}</ref>

